</p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#333333><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub97.ezboard.com/bnuclearspace.showLocalUserPublicProfile?login=cattlecar>cattlecar</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>NERVA Spaceplane Pilot</span><br>  Posts: 164<br> <font color=#6F6F6F>(6/19/02 9:35 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub97.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm1.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=534.topic&index=1>Reply</a>   <BR><img src=http://home.earthlink.net/~macami/ez/spinthingie.gif WIDTH=60 HEIGHT=60></td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> <img src="http://www.nuclearspace.com/ezboard/images/posticons/7.gif" align=absmiddle>  Re: Why are rockets so expensive?</span><hr size=1> Because they are (mostly) used once and thrown away.<br>
Imagine if you took a plane flight from Australia to California, USA.<br>
After the plane completed the flight they turned it into scrap metal.<br>
Granted, an airplane is a fairly complex piece of machinery, but it's<br>
a matter of re-usability.  Each time you are able to re-use the entire<br>
thing it becomes more cost effective.  Now the space shuttles have<br>
made many flights, and are 'apparently' re-usable.  But many systems<br>
are over-hauled or replaced after each flight.  Consider how much it<br>
would cost you to operate your automobile if you had to rebuild the<br>
engine after every 2 or 3 trips to the grocery store, or the local<br>
pub. So re-usability is a must.  Another possibility in lieu of<br>
re-usability, is economics of scale.  Perhaps if a reliable booster,<br>
even if used only once, was massed produced in a factory setting. <br>
Then economics of scale come into play.  The more you make, the<br>
cheaper each individual unit becomes, to a point.  Current boosters<br>
are practically hand built. This may sound like a better product, but<br>
compared to factory produced items, it's not.  Factory produced autos<br>
are generally much more reliable then hand built autos, their<br>
tolerances are generally much superior; they have to be for parts<br>
inter-changeability to work.  In world war II the Germans manufatured<br>
in excess of 3,000 V2 rockets (mostly with slave labor).  Imagine what<br>
could be accomplished in space with 3,000 Titan boosters, or 3,000<br>
Proton boosters, or 3,000 Energia boosters!  Even 3,000 is a low<br>
number compared to the millions of cars produced each year.  If a WWII<br>
production mentality was applied to a single type of rocket booster,<br>
then Mars would be colonized in no time.  Of course it would take<br>
something catastrophic to get the majority of the public behind such a<br>
program.  Just dreaming I guess. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#484848><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub97.ezboard.com/uprojectorion.showPublicProfile?language=EN>projectorion</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Nuclear Renaissance Man</span><br>  Posts: 1541<br> <font color=#6F6F6F>(6/20/02 4:17 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub97.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm1.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=534.topic&index=2>Reply</a>   <BR><img src=http://www.gothicbarbie.net/images/electric.gif WIDTH=60 HEIGHT=60></td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> <img src="http://www.nuclearspace.com/ezboard/images/posticons/7.gif" align=absmiddle>  Re: Why are rockets so expensive?</span><hr size=1> I read in an article that single stage nuclear launchers would be reusable. I guess that makes them even cheaper than I first imagined. Once you factor in the compacted energy of Uranium, long life of a reactor and plentiful supply of Hydrogen in space for propellant it's concievable that the ship might outlive it's pilots. <p>
<br><a href="http://pub97.ezboard.com/bnuclearspace"><img src="http://home.earthlink.net/~nuclearspace/website/images/title/title_03.jpg"> </a>
</p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#333333><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub97.ezboard.com/bnuclearspace.showLocalUserPublicProfile?login=atomicconspiracy>Atomic Conspiracy</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Moderator</span><br>  Posts: 128<br> <font color=#6F6F6F>(6/20/02 2:02 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub97.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm1.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=534.topic&index=3>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> <img src="http://www.nuclearspace.com/ezboard/images/posticons/7.gif" align=absmiddle>  Rockets</span><hr size=1> The technology of most of our current boosters is solidly rooted in the desperate money-no-object missile development race of the late 50s. The Titan and Atlas were originally ICBMs, the Delta is an outgrowth of the Thor IRBM. The Saturn rockets, which were purpose designed for space launches, use substantially this same technology. According to David Baker's <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> The Rocket</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END-->, even the giant F-1 first stage engine for the Saturn V and the LH2/LO2 upper stage engines were originally conceived for ballistic missiles. The Shuttle system is not so directly derived from missile technology but is still solidly rooted in it, and shares the same &quot;get it done at any cost&quot; assumptions that underlie the ballistic missile developments. Most of these early liquid-fuelled missiles were replaced by smaller solid propellent types within a few years, but their relatively large payloads suited them to space launches in the absence of any commitment to develop a truly specialized space launch technology. Given the largely political objectives of the space program in the 1960s, this made sense, but we have been stuck with a 1950s approach ever since. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#484848><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub97.ezboard.com/bnuclearspace.showLocalUserPublicProfile?login=x>X</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>NEP Freighter Crewman</span><br>  Posts: 82<br> <font color=#6F6F6F>(6/20/02 3:17 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub97.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm1.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=534.topic&index=4>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> <img src="http://www.nuclearspace.com/ezboard/images/posticons/7.gif" align=absmiddle>  Re: Why are rockets so expensive?</span><hr size=1> AC, it sounds like you're advocating the BDB (Big Dumb Booster) approach.  Robert Truax advocated using steel for building a rocket as opposed to expensive space age material and pressure-fed engines as opposed to turbo-pumps in order to reduce cost.  To make up for inefficiencies in the rocket, the rocket would be scaled up in size and launched at sea.  The ultimate conclusion of his idea was <!--EZCODE LINK START--><a href="http://www.astronautix.com/lvs/searagon.htm">Sea Dragon</a><!--EZCODE LINK END--> with a mass of 18,000 tons, a first stage engine with a thrust of 52 million pounds, and a payload capacity of over 500 tons, the Sea Dragon could have launch the entire ISS in one launch.  The cost per pound was estimated to be between $600 per kilogram (1/4 of the Saturn V) to $60 per kilograms (I'm assuming that this doesn't take into account inflation.  Even so, the upper limit would still be 1/8 of the Shuttle today).  There is also <!--EZCODE LINK START--><a href="http://www.smad.com/ie/ieframessr2.html">Microcosm</a><!--EZCODE LINK END--> and its family of Scorpius launch vehicles that rely on the same principles of KISS (Keep it simple, stupid). <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#333333><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub97.ezboard.com/utvyee1.showPublicProfile?language=EN>TVYee1</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Space Lurker</span><br>  Posts: 1<br> <font color=#6F6F6F>(6/26/02 11:02 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub97.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm1.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=534.topic&index=5>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> <img src="http://www.nuclearspace.com/ezboard/images/posticons/7.gif" align=absmiddle>  Re: Why are rockets so expensive?</span><hr size=1> I have to agree with the last two posts here.  The reason existing rockets are expensive is because someone spent a heck of a lot of money optimizing the heck out of them to squeeze extra ounces of performance out.  Couple that with the small market size for many of the niche products rocketry uses (how many 10&quot; LOX valves does a place like Guidance Dynamics make in a decade anyway, 10, 20?) and we've got a recipe for financial disaster.  Unfortunately, it's a vicious cycle, rockets are expensive so you have to optimize the heck out of em to get the most bang for your buck, but the systems are so expensive because so much engineering and optimization was done, and they've been customized to the hilt to get that performance so there are only a handful of suppliers willing to play in the market.  Of course, you can always further weed out price competition by being the federal government and having thousands of pages of regulations regarding how to buy toilet seats.<br>
<br>
The way to break the mold is to fanatically resist the temptation to overoptimize the systems.  I've been through the process once as program manager of AeroAstro's PA-X development program (we were competing head to head with Microcosm's Scorpius, though with different funding sources and different end users).  I can vouch for the fact that you can be successful if you stay singlemindedly focused on minimizing the bottom line for your application.  I think Microcosm is definitely properly focused in that respect, although I had concerns about the technical scalability of their plan (certain combustion chamber instabilities and technical difficulties only manifest themselves at higher pressures and larger sizes, so what works on a small rocket doesn't necessarily apply on a larger one unless they share the same critical engine parameters).  They may have addressed these issues since I was last involved in direct competition with them about 5 years ago.  I've interviewed with Bob Truax too, and he also has the right idea about how to keep costs contained, as well as some great, elegant, simplifying engineering solutions.  I'm not sure why no one in the air force hasn't thrown a pile of money at him yet, but maybe he's viewed as too much of a maverick, or maybe he doesn't play those political games as well as the Lockheed Martin's of the world.  Or maybe he just annoys the NASA engineers because his ideas have the audacity to be cheaper than NASA's by so much, so he obviously must not know what he's talking about.<br>
<br>
So, I wish these folks and others like them all the luck in the world.  They'll need it to successfully break the mold the industry has cast around itself. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#484848><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub97.ezboard.com/bnuclearspace.showLocalUserPublicProfile?login=x>X</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>NEP Freighter Crewman</span><br>  Posts: 85<br> <font color=#6F6F6F>(6/27/02 11:04 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub97.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm1.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=534.topic&index=6>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> <img src="http://www.nuclearspace.com/ezboard/images/posticons/radman.gif" align=absmiddle>  Re: Why are rockets so expensive?</span><hr size=1> Welcome to the club, TVYee1.  I hope you get something worthwhile from this messageboard.  So, you got to talk to Robert Truax, huh.  Would you consider posting your interview if you have anything written down from it.  There is also some work being done by Dick Rutan at <!--EZCODE LINK START--><a href="http://www.xcor.com/">XCOR</a><!--EZCODE LINK END--> on making a rocket-powered plane with a high rate of reliability.  The current estimate for space shuttle reliability is one catastroptic failure out of every hundred flights per shuttle.  The FAA wouldn't even tolerate one catastroptic failure out of every ten thousand flights per commerical airliner.  Dick Rutan knows if you want to make space travel routine, your launch vehicle's reliability must be better than what it is now. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#333333><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub97.ezboard.com/ustifled.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Stifled</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Space Tourist</span><br>  Posts: 5<br> <font color=#6F6F6F>(7/14/02 12:38 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub97.ezboard.