<br>
A nuclear engine may save about 1/2 to 2/3 on the fuel, but that is only part of the equation.<br>
<br>
1) A nuclear rocket has all the components of a combustion engine (tanks, fuel pumps, cooling systems, etc) PLUS nuclear reactors made of materials heavier than lead. In addition, crew shielding is needed. The fuel itself provides some sheild, but that is rapidly depleted. All designs include  massive shielding and/or the engines at very large distances from the payload - not suitable for a booster.<br>
<br>
2) Handling a reusable system would be a monumental task. Don't forget even with the engines off, the system would be as radioactive as dozens of giant civilian atomic power plants, yet be UNSHIELDED and with no containment. <br>
Even with the engines off the  reactors will be generating multi-gigawatts of heat. The system will require stupendous cooling. Imagine trying to do a fuel line repair (as is being done on the shuttle fleet) on a system emitting gigawatts of heat and giving off instantly lethal torrents of deeply penetrating radiation.<br>
<br>
3) The entire booster engine - rather than being a light weight disposable structure, will require ~massive~ re-entry protection capable of containing and shielding the whole system - even in the case of a worst-case accident. No spacecraft has ever been built to such standards.<br>
<br>
All this aside, you missed my main point. <br>
Any reasonable sized payload would require millions of pounds of thrust. As a rule of thumb. each million pound is equal to EIGHT nuclear power plants - or 16 gigawatts(t), or containing the fallout of 8,000 atomic bombs.<br>
<br>
Even if you factor in the fuel savings (and ignore all the added mass of the points above), you are boosting an unshielded, UNCONTAINED, machine equal to dozens of atomic plants thru the atmosphere and over the oceans and across the continents.  <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#484848><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub97.ezboard.com/bnuclearspace.showLocalUserPublicProfile?login=cattlecar>cattlecar</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>NERVA Spaceplane Pilot</span><br>  Posts: 242<br> <font color=#6F6F6F>(7/14/02 3:10 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub97.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm1.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=534.topic&index=10>Reply</a>   <BR><img src=http://home.earthlink.net/~macami/ez/spinthingie.gif WIDTH=60 HEIGHT=60></td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> <img src="http://www.nuclearspace.com/ezboard/images/posticons/spaceh.gif" align=absmiddle>  Nuclear boosters</span><hr size=1> I'm against most types of nuclear rockets launched from the ground.  Boosted into orbit, and then fire up a nuclear propulsion system is ok with me though. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#333333><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub97.ezboard.com/utmayes1965.showPublicProfile?language=EN>tmayes1965</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Space Cadet</span><br>  Posts: 38<br> <font color=#6F6F6F>(7/14/02 3:48 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub97.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm1.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=534.topic&index=11>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> <img src="http://www.nuclearspace.com/ezboard/images/posticons/spaceh.gif" align=absmiddle>  Re: Nuclear boosters</span><hr size=1> One 210,000 pound nuclear thermal propulsion space plane<br>
